 panic ills.\nNSr will one bo passed \"which will\ngfro relief to those who are respon\nsible for the financial panic of last\nyear find those who have been respon\nsible for all former financial panics.\nAs\" stated in this paper lasHDecem\nbejr. congress cannot and will not pro\nvfile for tha payment of tho debts of\ntCo country, corporate or individual,\nand wo must all agree that inability\ntd pay tho accumulated debts of the\ncountry fa what brings on panics.\nSanies are not hannful to the frugal\ncan who has avoided speculation and\ntho contracting, of debts which ho\ncould not pay; in fact, the frugal man\nwJlo has avoided financial obligations\nand aoroaches a financial panic with\na. cash surplus often finds the golden\noaportunlty for profitble investment,\nvthlio tho speculator, who has been\nplunging for abnormal profits on the\nstock board, soon finds thaj. he is\ndosed, out as bankrupt. After that\nthere ia nothing which congress can\ndo to restore that which he has lost\nla. his craze tor quick gain.\nTwo economia delusions long pos\nsessed- (he public mind, but both\nhave been dispelled by the October\nBasic of 1507. One was the fancy\nthat a financial depression and a pro\ntective tariff could not breathe the\nsarao air. and tha other was the hal\nlocinatlon that hard times could not\nexist; in tha presence of a large per\ncanlta escalation. Last October witnessed-\na frightful financial, commer-\ncfaX and Industrial depression, though\nalTlen ealoyel tho twin blessings\nol'hlgJL tariff and plenty of money.\nA business ganla Is tha child of\nIlqBlaation. Periodically pay day\ncomes' la tha business world, and\ntben. ft fa tha solvent and the bank-\ness: are separated. Prosperity comes\nterm, dUlgenco and thrift. Increased\ncirculation results from prosperity.\nSpeculation succeeds, to be followed\nby\" Crava& 05, luxury, and de\nbauchery. Then; business demands a\nsottlesenC That condition is what\njsaes rsnfira.\nTHE SHACKLES'.\nColllcr'a Weekly comes to the res\ncuozof tha dawn-trodden male creat\nure, and declares that wa must arise\nastLasaert our rights. Wa must pro\nclaim ouTsetvea free cf tha trammels\nof black and! white, eo long the pre\nser&ed and mournful gacb of evening\nfestivity, Wa mast, blossom forth in\nrjsrpio swallowtails. If not .purple.\nthen, nfafc.\nWould that it might be\n80?\nUfa la drab enough without\ndressing It tor x. Quaker part. Not\nthat, wo ouraetTes' yearn to emulate\ntha Illy, ot the field. But, tolling and\njewlEfnsr as- we must, we look with\nhigh hope to tho Umo when, conning\nour morning's paper, in \"tho season,\nwe shall miss the artistic details' of\nMrs. Homebody's Imported lsces ani\nillsa Otherbodys super-Imposed dia\nmonds, an In lieu thereof shall glad\nour eyes with something In this ten\nor: \"The Hon. Heigh Muyquo shone\nresplendent in a truly, national cS'\ntame, his coat being a spangle-of s(l-\nver stars upon a background of blue,\nwhile the emblematic design was car\nried out in brilliant but distasteful\nstripes of scarlet and white, running\nncthcrward.\" Or a description, in ef\nfect, as follows: \"A. Parrow Keete\nled the cotillion in a creation which\nIs destined to set a new fashion, the\ntails of tho coat being cut very long\nand chastely designed, the one In\nmauve, the other In old gold, with a\nwaistcoat of cerise polka-dots on a\nbodyground of pale pink color. The\nbottom of his trousers legs were\nfringed with bells, giving a toao of\nextreme -vivacity to this fetching co&\ntumo.\" Give the old man a chance.\nHis wife has monopolized It long\nenough.\n\nA \"SUCCESSFUL\" INDIAN.\nAs we pale faces estimate success\nin life, some ot the accomplishments\nof thered brother may not pass mus\nter, but that is largely a matter of\nrace. Indians no doubL estimate thPir\nfellows by whatthey\", have accoxn\nplished, and while c may not aii\nprove ot mo3t of the' accomplish-\nments, they make a great hit In he\ntepees. Take Chief Plenty Coos fo:\nIllustration. This noble red. man ap\npeared before the senate committee\non Indian affairs the other day and\nrepealed some of his personal his\ntory, which has resulted in making\nhim a great man among the Crow\ntribe.\nIn reply to questions, the chief ex\nplained that a \"coo\" was a stick- on\nwhich Indians strung their tropale\not war, otherwise scalps. In Cays\ngone by Chief Plenty Coos had no\ntrouble in filling his stick during a\ntomahawk fest with neighboring\ntribes, and was often compelled o get\nseveral more. Hence his namT\" So\ngreat was his success along this line\nof assassination and sca'p ripplug\nthat he commanded the -admiration of\nhis brothers. They made hlui a big\nchief and covered him with honors.\nAmong the Indians he was asgreat a\nman as a state go ernor among us.\nBut that isn't all that m-ido Plenty\nCoos a \"successful\" Indian. He was\nTtmU\nn H h. JP IB m en 1 81 al\nll OUlI\nIt seems to me, says Billy BuB,\nthat Hepburn Is all wrong,\ns Unless for Montreal a boom ho\nwants to help along\n'Cause thats where we will go\nto trade. Just to save the tax.\nIt with favor on his' arguments\nCongress ever sets.\nIV.\n\"SO both Egrccr that Hepburn, If\nhe gets his tax bill through,\nWill give the trains and steam-ships-lots\nand lots of things\nto do\nAnd with Walt street going to\nEngland they are both In-\ncllntd to think,\n'v Stock Exchange might welt\n3 be turned Into a skating rink.\nTHE BISBEE DAILY REVIEW,\nquite a squaws' man, having cap\ntured the hearts of no less than ten\ndusky maidens and married them,\nwithout regard to tha customs of the\nwhite man. This gained for him re\nnewed awo and rospect from his\ntribesmen, and his position as a suc\ncessful Jndlan was secure.\nAll of which Is chiefly Interesting\na showing the difference between\nraces in-the matter ot estimating'\nwhat consists ot success In lite. The\nhighly civilized pale face abhors mur\nder and bigamy. None of these\nthings for aim. But ho goeth torth\nwith designs on the bank roll ot his\nbrother, merely as a competitor In\nbusiness, or some such matter, there\nfore legitimately. If, figuratively\n\nspeasjng, ne inrows aowa ms w\npetitora and takes their money away\nfrom them, he is successful. Just as\nChief Plenty Coos was among his\npeople. Perhaps the world will yet\ndeielop a race that will look upon us\nas barbarians.\nP\nS OF y. M. G. k\nARE TALKED OVER\nMeeting Held at Tucson in In\nterest of Association of\nthe Souhtwest\nThero was a meeting attended by\nabout a score of gentlemen held at\nthe rooms ot the chamber .of com\nmerce In Tucson to discuss varlous\nplans for a Y. M. C. A. campaign ov\ner this section ot tho southwest The\nmeeting was held at the Instigation or\nC. K. Ober, the senior field secretary\nof the Y. M. C. A, international com\nmittee, who has come out from New\nYork for the purposo of aiding in the\nwork directly in hand, and by D W.\nPollard of Douglas, who Is In charge\nof tho field work for Arizona, New\nMexico, west Texas and Sonora.\nThere are'already thirty-four grand\ndivisions of the International Y. M. C.\nA. in thii country and with the com\npletion of the organization of this\none, the thirty-fifth and last one will\nhave been made up. The purpose of\nthe meeting was not to take any\nsteps at this time, looking to the org-\nanlzatioh of a local In Tucson, out to\nstart the work and arrange ultimate-1\nly for the appointment of two gentle-l\nmen from that city, who, with repre-j\nsentalives from the other towns of'\nthe section, will constitute a general\ncommittee over the territory: Funds\nare to be raised for the work and tho\nmatter of their solicitation has been\nplaced in charge of \"President\nBabcock of the University of Arizona,\n.aics-ii-, ijuci uuu ruiiaiu outicu\nthat there are now but six locals inwlll have charge of the work. That\nthis sectl6a-Las Vegas, Douglas, El is not at all imminent and may not\nPaso. Blsbee, Phoenix and Deming. be undertaken for the next year or\nTh ,r flftonn oiM intho soinn two.\nThere are fifteen cities In the section\nAN\nADVENTURES IN\nJp- -il---\nIt worries i\no\nIL\n,&3S\nJvaHmS Aft J&f\nBISBEE, ARIZONA, SATURDAY\nr;\nSTORIES OF\nTHE CANYON\nBy the Burro.\ns'srvsysrj\nOut in Warren a happy bunch of\nCalumet Arizona engineers have\nrented a cottage, where they bunk in i\ntrue bachelor style, taking their\nmeals at a restaurant near by.\nTho inhabitants of the new metro\npolls of Arizona have discovered some\npleasing things about the boys. One\nof them is that the only reason they\nare not grand opera singers Is be\ncause they have something better\nwith tho big mining company. Those\nboys can sing, all right, and don't I\nyou forget iL When they have a con-'\ncert among themselves, the neighbors\nfor a block or two around find some\nbusiness in the immediate vicinity.\nThe other night the saengerfest saen-i\neerfested iH kont scores of neonle\nV-;,',, h h\nxrw.\nMid not know they were being listen-\ncu to. -uu juuug wtrio cutuiacu, nuu\nine old tat:en dock to youm. as tne\nvoices blended perfectly In good old\nsongs, such as\n\"Backward, turn backward, O TImo\nIn jour flight,\n\"Backward, turn hackward, O\n-Jlmo In your flight;\n,Make mo a child again, just\nfor tonight i\nMother, come back from tne\nEcholess Shore,\nTake me again to your heart\nas of yore:\nKiss from my forehead the\nfurrows of care.\nOver my slumbers your lov\ning watch keep.\nRock mo to \"sleep, mother,\nrock me to sleep'\nThen would come some good, red\nblooded college song, succeeded by\n\"Way down on de Suwaneo ribber\nFar, far away.\nDats where my heart am turning ebber,\nDats where de old folks stay. j\nSlowly the listeners dispersed at the\nend. \"Where did Col. Powell get those\nboys?\" commented ono. \"Let's send\nhim a vote ot thanks.\"\nThe only point of resemblance be\ntween Morris Marks, the Lowell mer\nchant. and a Gila monster ti that both\nwould like to have warm weather in'\nthis latitude right away. \"Don't you\nwish It would get warm?\" asked the\nBurro ot Mr. Marks. \"Now you are\ntalking sense, you long earned brute,\"\nwas the reply. \"Warm weather! Why\nwheiiv I see It coming over the hill\nfrom Bakersville. I am going to meet\nit with the South Blsbee band and a\nbarbecue!\"\nJ\nFIGHTING BOB EVANS'\nFleet on exhibition this afternoon\nand evening at tho Royal. Admis\nsion 15c\nReview \"Wtr Ads. bring results.\nwhich within the next two years, It is\nhoped to Include. Aside from Tuc-\nson, these are Prescott, Globe, Clif-\nton-Morencl, Albuquerque, Roswell,\nRaton, Santa Fe, Cananea, Nacozarl,\nNogales and others.\nWhen the time comes when it is\nthought possible to start a building\ncampaign In the Old Pueblo, the com-\nj.i.t- uciuj, uuc w,\ntwo.\nWAIL TRI\nmini ,m\nBilly Bull end Bertie Bear ss\nday 's' succeeded day\nAce worrying about the act or\ntilia-From-loviay,\nWho's Introduced In Washington\nbefore the House of Reps.,\nThe flfty-ccnts-a-share bill that\nWall street'll know as 'Hep's.'\nme, says Ber\"c Bear,\nJust as much as j ou,\n'Cause I'd have to go to London\nto put all my trading through,\nAnd I must say Wall streefs\nbetter for attempting such a\ntrick;\nBecause In stormy weather water\ntravel makes me sick.\nMORNING, APRIL 11, 1908\nI\nJ\"\ni tiki BANK OF BlS-JKht\ni i s\nI I -T-\nii KI-KHH. W I J I 1M Kronnh-f ll-,--.o-H ,nnra\n'1 i-U WHii J1B11UIU A1Bl,W OllU uc\nOFFICERS:\nW. H. Bjp$hy, president\nJ. S. Dcuglat, Vice-President.\nM. J. Cunningham, Cashier.\nH. A. Schwartz, Asa't Cashier.\ns\nWe' Have Unequaled Facilities for Care\ntVHf III MtmmftTMtmtttmtMV-i\n-AJiiMiniiMnii imiiiM!iiii;L\nz\n\nIF YOU WANT\nA GOOD POSITION 3\n5 CALL AT THE 3\nSouthwestern 3\nCoHection and 3\nEmployment Agency 3\nRoom 2. MUHEIM BLDQ.\nPhone 164. 3\nzmmuumiimuummuuure\ns-\nJ rtrwjssjfMSjrsssstr\nJOHN W. H0GAN\nx\nJustice ot tho Peace Notary.\n.Deputy Coroner Precinct No. 2.\nREAL ESTATE\nRENTALS\nCOLLECTIONS\nMARRIAGE LICENSES.\nCor. Subway and J. E. T. StreeL\nTelephone 271. Bl